'''Choi Yun-chil''' (born July 19, 1928) is a former [[South Korea]]n long-distance runner who was a two-time [[Olympian]]<ref>http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ch/choi-yun-chil-1.html</ref> and a two-time national champion in the [[marathon]].<ref>http://www.arrs.net/NC_MaraKOR.htm</ref>

Choi led the marathon at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]] before dropping out with less than 5 kilometers left in the race.<ref name="Martin">{{cite book|last=Martin|first=David E.|coauthors=Roger W. H. Gynn|title=The Olympic Marathon|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Qb125O62NVQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Human Kinetics Publishers |date=May 2000|page=188|isbn=978-0880119696}}</ref> He finished third in the 1950 [[Boston Marathon]]<ref>http://www.arrs.net/MaraRank/ATM_Mara1950.htm</ref><ref name="Time1">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,812351,00.html Sport: Koreans in a Hurry.] ''Time'', May 1, 1950.</ref>, but the [[Boston Athletic Association]] denied his entry into the follow year's event.<ref name="Time2">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,820682,00.html Sport: Banned in Boston.] ''Time'', February 12, 1951.</ref> During the height of the [[Korean War]], BAA President [[Walter A. Brown]] stated: "While American soldiers are fighting and dying in Korea, every Korean should be fighting to protect his country instead of training for marathons. As long as the war continues there, we positively will not accept Korean entries for our race on April 19."<ref name="Time2"/> In 1952, Choi would finish 4th in the [[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's marathon|Olympic marathon at Helsinki]].<ref name="Martin">{{cite book|last=Martin|first=David E.|coauthors=Roger W. H. Gynn|title=The Olympic Marathon|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Qb125O62NVQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Human Kinetics Publishers |date=May 2000|pages=205-207|isbn=978-0880119696}}</ref>

